docs.abstract: If courts are to combat voting districts warped by politics, a judge wrote, they must take account of advances in social science.
docs.snippet: If courts are to combat voting districts warped by politics, a judge wrote, they must take account of advances in social science.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — In October, when the Supreme Court heard arguments in a case that could reshape American politics, Chief Justice John G. Roberts Jr. registered an objection. There was math in the case, he said, and it was complicated.

headline.main: A Case for Math, Not ‘Gobbledygook,’ in Judging Partisan Voting Maps
headline.print_headline: To Test if a Voting Map Is Partisan, Do the Math

docs.abstract: Matt Mika was badly wounded during last summer’s attack on the Republican congressional baseball team. Nearly every hour brings a reminder of what he can no longer do.
docs.snippet: Matt Mika was badly wounded during last summer’s attack on the Republican congressional baseball team. Nearly every hour brings a reminder of what he can no longer do.
docs.lead_paragraph: ALEXANDRIA, Va. — Exactly a month after Matt Mika was shot while practicing for a baseball game, he drove with his father to the field here where he once lay dying, his face yellowing, then graying, his eyes lifeless.

headline.main: Resisting the Label of Victim, but Forever Scarred by a Mass Shooting
headline.print_headline: Wounded in a Mass Shooting, He Resists the Label of Victim

docs.abstract: John F. Kelly told Hispanic members of Congress on Wednesday that President Trump’s campaign promises have “evolved” on immigration.
docs.snippet: John F. Kelly told Hispanic members of Congress on Wednesday that President Trump’s campaign promises have “evolved” on immigration.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — President Trump’s chief of staff privately told a group of Democratic lawmakers on Wednesday that Mr. Trump had not been “fully informed” when promising voters a wall along the Mexican border last year, and said that he had persuaded the president it was not necessary. He also expressed optimism that a bipartisan immigration deal could eventually be reached.

headline.main: Trump Was Not ‘Fully Informed’ in Campaign Vows on Wall, Chief of Staff Says
headline.print_headline: Trump Was Not ‘Fully Informed’ In 2016 Vow on Wall, Kelly Says

byline.original: By Julie Hirschfeld Davis, Sheryl Gay Stolberg and Thomas Kaplan

docs.abstract: President Trump’s trip to the World Economic Forum is raising eyebrows in Washington given the event’s reputation as a retreat for the “globalists” he disdains.
docs.snippet: President Trump’s trip to the World Economic Forum is raising eyebrows in Washington given the event’s reputation as a retreat for the “globalists” he disdains.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — President Trump’s decision to attend the World Economic Forum, a global gathering of industry titans, government ministers, celebrities, activists and others at the mountain resort of Davos, Switzerland, raised eyebrows in Washington, given Mr. Trump’s professed disdain for the “globalists” who typically attend the retreat.

headline.main: Global Elite? At Davos? That’s News to Mnuchin
headline.print_headline: Global Elite  At Davos? That’s News To Mnuchin

docs.abstract: Several governors, mostly Republicans, have declined to sign their own states’ plans for implementing a new federal education law intended to devolve control to the states.
docs.snippet: Several governors, mostly Republicans, have declined to sign their own states’ plans for implementing a new federal education law intended to devolve control to the states.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — The majority of states now have the green light from Education Secretary Betsy DeVos to begin implementing a sweeping federal law passed in 2015 to replace the much-maligned No Child Left Behind law.

headline.main: As DeVos Approves Education Plans, She Finds Skeptics in G.O.P. Governors
headline.print_headline: As DeVos Signs Education Plans, She Finds Skeptics in G.O.P. Governors

docs.abstract: President Trump will call this week for a $1.5 trillion infrastructure initiative by matching up to $100 billion in funds that states and cities put toward infrastructure projects.
docs.snippet: President Trump will call this week for a $1.5 trillion infrastructure initiative by matching up to $100 billion in funds that states and cities put toward infrastructure projects.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — President Trump on Monday will propose offering $100 billion in federal incentives to encourage cities and states to invest in road, bridge and other building projects, the centerpiece of a plan to spur $1.5 trillion in infrastructure spending over the next decade without devoting significant federal money.

headline.main: Trump’s Infrastructure Plan: Modest Federal Incentives, Facing Long Odds
headline.print_headline: Trump’s Plan To Finance Infrastructure Faces Hurdles

docs.abstract: “I have been heartened to see children across this country using their voices,” Mrs. Trump said of the students, many of whom have pushed for gun measures her husband has resisted.
docs.snippet: “I have been heartened to see children across this country using their voices,” Mrs. Trump said of the students, many of whom have pushed for gun measures her husband has resisted.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — In rare public remarks on Monday, the first lady, Melania Trump, voiced support for the student-led demonstrations that have unfolded after a school shooting left 17 dead in Parkland, Fla., many of which have called for gun restrictions her husband has resisted.

headline.main: Melania Trump Offers Support for Student Protesters After Florida Shooting
headline.print_headline: Students ‘Deserve a Voice,’ First Lady Says of Protests

docs.abstract: Mike Pompeo, President Trump’s choice for secretary of state, won’t be able to contact South Koreans, let alone North Koreans, until the Senate approves his nomination.
docs.snippet: Mike Pompeo, President Trump’s choice for secretary of state, won’t be able to contact South Koreans, let alone North Koreans, until the Senate approves his nomination.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — The White House has created a working group to prepare for the landmark meeting between President Trump and Kim Jong-un of North Korea. But Mr. Trump’s sudden ousting on Tuesday of Secretary of State Rex W. Tillerson could delay critical elements of the planning until the Senate confirms his successor, Mike Pompeo.

headline.main: Cabinet Changes Could Delay Planning for Meeting with Kim Jong-un
headline.print_headline: Cabinet Changes Could Delay Kim Meeting

docs.abstract: Mr. Carson, the HUD secretary, had said the decision was handled by subordinates. But a message refers to “printouts of the furniture the secretary and Mrs. Carson picked out.”
docs.snippet: Mr. Carson, the HUD secretary, had said the decision was handled by subordinates. But a message refers to “printouts of the furniture the secretary and Mrs. Carson picked out.”
docs.lead_paragraph: Ben Carson, the secretary of housing and urban development, and his wife were directly involved in selecting a $31,000 custom mahogany dining room set for his office — contrary to Mr. Carson’s claim that the decision was handled by subordinates, newly obtained documents show.

headline.main: Emails Contradict Ben Carson’s Claims About $31,000 Dining Set for Office
headline.print_headline: Documents Contradict Official Line On Dining Set

docs.abstract: Voters who turned out for Donald Trump in 2016 appeared to turn on his chosen House candidate Tuesday, helping Conor Lamb, the Democrat, take a slight lead.
docs.snippet: Voters who turned out for Donald Trump in 2016 appeared to turn on his chosen House candidate Tuesday, helping Conor Lamb, the Democrat, take a slight lead.
docs.lead_paragraph: LOS ANGELES — President Trump woke up here in the land of earthquakes on Wednesday morning, but he was 2,500 miles away from the tremor that was really shaking his party.

headline.main: Strong Performance by Democrat Conor Lamb in Pennsylvania Shakes Trump and G.O.P.

byline.original: By Peter Baker and Michael D. Shear
